The losers remain challengers.
HARARE: Before this month's presidential elections, I was convinced that irregularities would have serious consequences in Zimbabwe itself and across southern Africa.
Despite the shadows of war and terrorism, I called for fair and free elections.
The people of Zimbabwe did not get it.
Instead, they received terror.
In the two years leading up to the presidential elections, the people of Zimbabwe were subjected to intimidation, harassment and threats by the party of Robert Mugabe, the Zimbabwe African National Union - Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF), whose programme is state-sponsored terrorism.
The ZANU terror is on the account of the rogue elements among the veterans of Zimbabwe's independence war over two decades ago, government militias and young men who are all supported by the police.
Consequence of intimidation and violence was that my party, the Movement for Democratic Change (MDC), did not reach the electorate in large parts, especially in rural areas at all.
In addition, the government of my opponent, President Mugabe, has effectively disenfranchised hundreds of thousands of voters in the cities, particularly in the capital Harare and Chitungwiza.
Since there were not enough polling stations overall, I believe that more than 360,000 people in Harare and Chitungwiza alone stood in line without being able to cast their ballots.
I continue to question the legitimacy of the election result because Mugabe's militias prevented MDC observers from being stationed at 52% of rural polling stations.
At the end of the vote-counting process, observers for our party were missing in 6 out of 10 polling stations in the countryside.
That means Mugabe's followers could impose their will in these polling stations.
We are currently compiling a comprehensive list of all the polling stations that were only controlled by ZANU supporters.
In our previous investigations, even at this early stage, a system has emerged: in these polling stations, most votes have been cast for Mugabe.
In light of the overwhelming evidence, I cannot accept the result of the presidential elections, in which the incumbent President Robert Mugabe emerged as the winner, having received 56% of the 3 million cast votes.
The official result does not reflect the true will of the people of Zimbabwe and is illegitimate in their eyes.
The people of Zimbabwe were deprived of their right to freely and democratically elect a president of their choice.
The fight for the election results is a political matter that must be politically resolved.
Food and fuel are scarce, jobs are being lost, inflation is over 100%.
The people of Zimbabwe were brave and resolute and deserve to be acknowledged for this.
Maybe it's not too late for that yet.
I am writing this text in dismay, because Mugabe's regime still disregards the will of the people.
Whatever happens, I will stand by the people as a faithful servant and see the path through with them.
Possibly, the government will arrest me.
I was also arrested for treason before the elections.
In the worst-case scenario, they even want to kill me.
But the government will never be able to break the people's will, their rights, and their power.
It is up to us to bring about a democratic change.
In the coming days, we will experience moments of fear, but we must not allow despair to overwhelm us.
The political change is unstoppable.
But we must be prepared to pay a high price for our freedom.
President Mugabe and his henchmen are afraid of the people, and we have heard that they will do everything to kill the bearer of the message.
If it comes to that, I would ask the people of Zimbabwe only to remain strong and to finish what we have started together.
There are many heroes in the people of Zimbabwe - heroes who waited for hours to vote, heroes who were not chased away.
They are the heroes of a new Zimbabwe, whose voices must be heard in the world.
We have walked a very rocky road together in order to achieve a democratic change in our country.
In the history of humanity, a nation rarely had to endure such violence and yet managed to preserve kindness and exuberance.
I notice that the population of Zimbabwe is impatient.
I understand that.
But for there to be a political process, they must be patient and wait.
They can't just leave these elections alone, but they also shouldn't fall into the provocation of Mugabe and resort to violence.
The people of Zimbabwe want change, in the constitution, in the justice system, legitimate change, and they will achieve it, despite all obstacles.
We know that we are not alone.
We know that in all of Africa, people are cheated during elections.
Irregularities, fraud and election rigging seem to be the norm in most African countries.
There is always some crisis somewhere in Africa because of elections.
It is sad, but the entire continent is plagued by governments that resort to unfair means when it's time to grant people their right to vote.
But those who want something else can hope.
Zimbabwe's struggle is not yet over.
There is still time to draw lessons for Africa and the world from our experience.
My people are in the hour of their greatest need.
I promise not to leave it.
